Morphological studies revealed that the collected samples belonged to a new species of Botryanthus (Kunth) Rouy (1910: 435) subgenus, with features such as the flower structure being globose, filaments arranged in double rows, and the leaves being patent. In the original publication of Muscari pallens ( Bieberstein 1808 )
, it is also reported that the leaves are linear lanceolate, the perigone is cylindric-campanulate, the tube is shorter, the lobes are erect to tubes as positional and slightly minute erect. Additionally, when the picture in Edinburgh ( E ), which is thought to belong to the type, and a suspicious sample given as a syntype in the Moscow herbarium ( MW ) are examined; the leaves are 2 or 3, oblanceolate and fertile flowers are cylindiric-campanulate as described in the protolog. Moreover, the leaves are described as linear but slightly enlarged upwards in Russian flora. Finally, when the Muscari pallens samples in different international herbariums were examined [ E , MW (digital), G !;
] it was seen that the fertile flowers were cylindiric-campanulate, and the leaves were less than four, oblanceolate and ascending. As we know, cylindiric-campanulat periant are mostly related to the subgenus PseudomuscariGarbari & Greuter (1970: 334) and even, Pseudomuscari is considered a separate genus ( Garbari & Greuter 1970 ). Thus, it has been concluded that the samples collected from Van city are very different from other taxa of Turkey and from especially M. pallens , so they are belonging to a new Turkish Muscari species
(Sect. Botryanthus ). The new species is similar with M. armeniacum and M. botryoides in terms of morphological features. It has darker brown bulb tunics; less fertile flowers and its pedicels are more pendulous or shorter; fertile flowers are usually whitish lilac or ice blue and clearly smaller, the fruit are almost obcordate (
and
).

